column7: Physiologically based pharmacokinetic (PBPK) modeling is a mathematical modeling technique that predicts the absorption, distribution, metabolism, and excretion (ADME) of synthetic or natural chemical substances in humans and other animal species
column8: Physiologically based pharmacokinetic (PBPK) modeling is a mathematical modeling technique that predicts the absorption, distribution, metabolism, and excretion (ADME) of synthetic or natural chemical substances in humans and other animal species

column7: A whole-body PBPK model contains an explicit representation of the organs that are most relevant to the absorption, distribution, excretion, and metabolization of the drug/chemicals due to their physiological/pharmacological function or their volume
column8: A whole-body PBPK model contains an explicit representation of the organs that are most relevant to the absorption, distribution, excretion, and metabolization of the drug/chemicals due to their physiological/pharmacological function or their volume

column7: Perfusion-limited models are a type of physiologically based pharmacokinetic (PBPK) model that assumes that the concentration of a substance in tissues reaches equilibrium with the substance in the circulation rapidly. In perfusion-limited models, the rate of drug uptake by tissues is limited by blood flow, and the rate of drug elimination is limited by the rate of diffusion from the tissue to the blood
column8: Perfusion-limited models are a type of physiologically based pharmacokinetic (PBPK) model that assumes that the concentration of a substance in tissues reaches equilibrium with the substance in the circulation rapidly. In perfusion-limited models, the rate of drug uptake by tissues is limited by blood flow, and the rate of drug elimination is limited by the rate of diffusion from the tissue to the blood
